{"timestamp": "2026-03-12T07:00:40.950060", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_claude/Glycine-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_claude", "raw_response": "# Prebiotic glycine synthesis: a complete pathway atlas for origin of life chemistry\n\n**Glycine, the simplest amino acid, emerges through at least ten distinct prebiotic routes spanning every plausible early Earth environment \u2014 from spark-discharge atmospheres to alkaline hydrothermal vents to interstellar ices.** This convergence from multiple independent pathways explains why glycine is consistently the most abundant amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments, carbonaceous meteorites, and cometary samples alike. The synthesis network is anchored by three master precursors \u2014 HCN, formaldehyde, and ammonia \u2014 whose reactions with each other and with mineral catalysts generate glycine through Strecker synthesis, HCN polymer hydrolysis, reductive amination, photochemistry, and Fischer-Tropsch-type catalysis. Understanding these interconnected pathways, their environmental requirements, kinetic bottlenecks, and shared intermediates is essential for computationally modeling prebiotic chemistry networks.\n\n---\n\n## The Strecker synthesis remains the dominant pathway to prebiotic glycine\n\nThe Strecker synthesis \u2014 formaldehyde + HCN + ammonia \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine \u2014 is the single most important route to prebiotic glycine, operating as the principal mechanism in Miller-Urey experiments, meteorite parent bodies, and potentially in interstellar ices. Stanley Miller himself identified this as the mechanism underlying his 1953 spark discharge results (Miller, 1953, *Science* 117:528\u2013529; Miller, 1957, *Biochimica et Biophysica Acta*).\n\nThe mechanism proceeds through four steps with well-characterized energetics. First, ammonia attacks formaldehyde to produce aminomethanol (NH\u2082CH\u2082OH), which dehydrates to methanimine (CH\u2082=NH). Cyanide then adds to the imine, yielding aminoacetonitrile (NH\u2082CH\u2082CN). Finally, hydrolysis proceeds through glycinamide (NH\u2082CH\u2082CONH\u2082) to glycine. Ab initio molecular dynamics simulations by Magrino, Pietrucci, and Saitta (2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters* 12:2630\u20132637) mapped the complete free energy landscape in explicit aqueous solution: glycinonitrile formation has a rate-limiting barrier of **15 kcal/mol**, nitrile hydration to glycinamide requires **23 kcal/mol**, and the final amide hydrolysis to glycine faces the highest barrier at **31 kcal/mol**. The overall reaction is strongly exergonic, with glycine at **\u221237 kcal/mol** relative to initial reactants.\n\nA critical alternative exists through the **Bucherer-Bergs pathway**, where aminoacetonitrile reacts with CO\u2082 (abundant in the early atmosphere) to form hydantoin, which hydrolyzes to N-carbamoyl-glycine, then to glycine. Taillades, Commeyras, and colleagues (1998, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 28:61\u201377) demonstrated that under realistic prebiotic conditions \u2014 [HCN] and [HCHO] ~1 g/L, pH 8, 25\u00b0C, low [NH\u2083] \u2014 the system produces 99.9% glycolonitrile and only 0.1% aminoacetonitrile. However, CO\u2082 catalyzes conversion of that small aminoacetonitrile fraction to hydantoin, shifting equilibrium productively. Pulletikurti et al. (2022, *Nature Chemistry*) achieved **80% hydantoin yield** from pyruvate + cyanide + ammonia in bicarbonate buffer at room temperature, demonstrating this pathway bridges prebiotic aldehyde chemistry and modern metabolism.\n\n---\n\n## Miller-Urey experiments and their modern reanalyses reveal far richer chemistry than originally appreciated\n\nMiller's original 1953 experiment \u2014 continuous spark discharge through CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082 for one week \u2014 identified five amino acids, with **glycine as the most abundant at ~1.05% of total carbon** (Miller, 1955, *Journal of the American Chemical Society*). The mechanism was purely chemical: sparks produced HCN and aldehydes in the gas phase, which dissolved and underwent Strecker synthesis in the aqueous flask.\n\nThe 2008 reanalysis by Jeffrey Bada's group transformed our understanding. After Miller's death in 2007, Bada inherited sealed sample vials from three distinct experimental setups. Using modern HPLC-MS and UPLC-ToF-MS, Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322:404) found that the classic experiment actually produced **14 amino acids and 5 amines** \u2014 far more than Miller's 1950s-era paper chromatography could detect. A previously unpublished volcanic spark discharge apparatus, using a steam-aspirating nozzle simulating volcanic lightning, yielded **22 amino acids and 5 amines**, many hydroxylated. Most remarkably, Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) reanalyzed Miller's 1958 H\u2082S-containing experiment and found **23 amino acids, 4 amines, and 7 organosulfur compounds** \u2014 with amino acid distributions that correlated remarkably well with carbonaceous chondrite abundances.\n\nThe atmospheric composition debate profoundly affects these yields. Under strongly reducing conditions (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082), glycine yields reach several percent of total carbon. Under neutral CO\u2082/N\u2082/H\u2082O atmospheres, yields plummet by orders of magnitude \u2014 though Cleaves et al. (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 38:105\u2013115) showed that adding ferrous iron as an oxidation inhibitor during hydrolysis substantially increased detected amino acids, suggesting previous low yields from neutral atmospheres were partly analytical artifacts. Schlesinger and Miller (1983, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*) demonstrated that **CO-containing atmospheres yield bioorganic compounds comparable to strongly reducing atmospheres**, an important finding since CO is geochemically more plausible than CH\u2084 as a long-lived atmospheric constituent.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents, serpentinization, and iron-sulfur mineral catalysis provide submarine routes to glycine\n\nTwo fundamentally different hydrothermal environments offer glycine synthesis potential, with alkaline vents dramatically more favorable than black smokers.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City type) operate at **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with H\u2082 concentrations up to **15 mmol/kg** generated by serpentinization of olivine. The Russell-Martin-Lane model proposes these vents as the cradle of prebiotic chemistry: natural pH gradients of ~5 units across thin Fe(Ni)S mineral barriers between alkaline vent fluid and the mildly acidic Hadean ocean (pH ~5.5) create electrochemical potentials of ~180 mV \u2014 directly analogous to biological chemiosmotic coupling. Wimmer et al. (2021) calculated that **97% of the ~400 reactions needed to synthesize amino acids, nucleobases, and cofactors are exergonic** under serpentinizing vent conditions.\n\nThe mineral catalysis results are striking. **Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 4:534\u2013542)** demonstrated that greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084), and awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) catalyze CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 formate (up to **200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M), and methanol (~100 \u00b5M) at 100\u00b0C under alkaline conditions. Even more remarkably, **Beyazay et al. (2023, *Nature Communications* 14:570)** showed Ni\u2083Fe nanoparticles catalyze CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate and citramalate at just **25\u00b0C under 25 bar** \u2014 room temperature catalysis on a mineral that forms naturally in serpentinizing systems.\n\nThe path from these C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 intermediates to glycine proceeds via reductive amination. **Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116:4828\u20134833)** demonstrated that pyruvate + NH\u2083 + mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides produces alanine, with maximum yield at **1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio** and alkaline pH. A landmark 2024 study in *PNAS* (doi:10.1073/pnas.2408248121) showed that **ferroan brucite** [Fe\u2080.\u2083\u2083Mg\u2080.\u2086\u2087(OH)\u2082] mediates glycine synthesis from nitrate + glyoxylate, with up to **97% of produced glycine partitioned to the mineral fraction** \u2014 demonstrating both synthesis and concentration in a single mineral system. This finding is particularly significant because it expands plausible prebiotic environments to include oxidizing atmospheres where nitrate is stable.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133) face a fundamental problem: glycine's thermal stability. Aqueous glycine decomposes via decarboxylation (\u2192 methylamine + CO\u2082) and deamination (\u2192 glycolic acid + NH\u2083), with activation energy **Ea \u2248 95.9\u2013156 kJ/mol** (Sato et al., 2004). At 200\u00b0C, ~90% of amino acids decompose; at 250\u00b0C, the half-life drops to minutes. The thermal optimum for glycine dimerization is **pH 9.8, 140\u00b0C**, with Ea = 88 kJ/mol (Sakata et al., 2010, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 74:6841\u20136851). These data strongly favor alkaline vents over black smokers for sustained amino acid chemistry.\n\nW\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis proposed that the exergonic formation of pyrite (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082, **\u0394G = \u22129.2 to \u221210.0 kcal/mol**) could drive prebiotic carbon fixation. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, *Science* 276:245\u2013247) demonstrated thioester synthesis from CO + CH\u2083SH on FeS/NiS at 100\u00b0C, and subsequently showed peptide bond formation from amino acids activated with CO on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces (1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672). However, the proposed full autocatalytic reductive citric acid cycle on FeS surfaces has not been experimentally demonstrated, and Schoonen et al. (1999) could not replicate citric acid synthesis from CO\u2082 on FeS catalysts.\n\n---\n\n## HCN polymers, cyanosulfidic chemistry, and Fischer-Tropsch catalysis provide additional convergent pathways\n\n**HCN polymerization** represents a distinct route to glycine that bypasses the Strecker synthesis entirely. HCN oligomerizes through a base-catalyzed pathway: dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 trimer (aminomalononitrile, AMN) \u2192 tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2192 higher polymers. The rate-determining dimerization step has k = **0.096 L mol\u207b\u00b9 day\u207b\u00b9** at pH 9.2 and 40\u00b0C (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966, *Science* 153:72). A critical threshold exists: polymerization is fourth-order in HCN while hydrolysis is first-order, so polymerization dominates only above **0.01\u20130.1 M HCN** (Sanchez et al., 1967, *Journal of Molecular Biology* 30:223). Since oceanic HCN at 100\u00b0C and pH 8 reaches only ~7 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 32:209), eutectic concentration by freezing to **\u221223.4\u00b0C** (producing **74.5 mol% HCN** eutectic) is likely required.\n\nAcid or base hydrolysis of HCN polymers yields **glycine as the most abundant product under all 23 experimental conditions tested** (Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013, *Life* 3:421), alongside up to 24 amino acids total, including **12 of the 20 protein amino acids**. Or\u00f3's pioneering work in the early 1960s first demonstrated this, heating 0.1\u20132.2 M ammoniacal HCN at 70\u00b0C for 25 days. Matthews and Moser (1966, *PNAS* 56:1087) proposed that HCN polymerizes directly to polyaminomalononitrile and thence to heteropolypeptides without free amino acid intermediates \u2014 a controversial hypothesis challenged by Ferris (1979, *Science* 203:1135) but never fully resolved.\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry** represents the most elegant systems chemistry approach. Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307) demonstrated that HCN + H\u2082S + UV light + phosphate buffer at 35\u00b0C produces precursors to amino acids, ribonucleotides, and lipids simultaneously through a unified network. The mechanism involves Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox cycling driving reductive homologation of HCN, with H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant. Aminoacetonitrile (glycine precursor), 2-aminopropanenitrile (alanine precursor), and sugar precursors emerge as inevitable products of the same network. As Patel et al. noted, \"biology did not select all of its building blocks, but was simply presented with a specific set as a consequence of the (photo)chemistry of hydrogen cyanide and hydrogen sulfide.\"\n\n**Fischer-Tropsch type (FTT) synthesis** operates through CO + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 on metallic catalysts at 360\u2013600\u00b0C. Yoshino, Hayatsu, and Anders (1971, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 35:927\u2013938) first demonstrated amino acid synthesis including glycine on meteoritic iron catalysts. The mechanism involves FTT generation of formaldehyde and HCN on catalyst surfaces, followed by Strecker synthesis in cooler zones. In a CO-rich early atmosphere, native iron and FeNi particles could produce up to **7 \u00d7 10\u2079 to 5 \u00d7 10\u00b9\u00b2 kg/yr** of HCN and other organics.\n\n---\n\n## Glycine is ubiquitous in the solar system \u2014 from meteorites to comets to laboratory ice analogs\n\n**The Murchison meteorite** (CM2 carbonaceous chondrite, fell September 28, 1969, Australia) contains **>90 amino acids** at concentrations of ~3 ppm for glycine (~150\u2013250 nmol/g). Isotopic analysis provides definitive evidence of extraterrestrial origin: \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C values reach **+40\u2030** for amino acids (vs. terrestrial values typically <\u221220\u2030), with \u03b4D up to **+2,500\u2030** and near-racemic D/L ratios confirming abiotic synthesis (Cronin & Pizzarello, 1983; Pizzarello et al., 2004; Glavin & Dworkin, 2009, *PNAS* 106:5487). CR2 chondrites show even higher total amino acid concentrations, up to **~715 nmol/g** in some samples. The Strecker synthesis on aqueous parent bodies is supported by the dominance of \u03b1-amino acids and parallel production of \u03b1-hydroxy acids via the cyanohydrin pathway.\n\nCometary glycine was confirmed by two independent missions. The NASA **Stardust** spacecraft returned samples from Comet 81P/Wild 2 in 2006; Elsila, Glavin, and Dworkin (2009, *Meteoritics & Planetary Science* 44:1323\u20131330) detected glycine with extraterrestrial \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C signatures on collector surfaces. The ESA **Rosetta** mission directly measured glycine in the coma gas of Comet 67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko using the ROSINA mass spectrometer (Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances* 2:e1600285), along with methylamine and ethylamine (glycine precursors) and the first cometary detection of phosphorus.\n\n**Interstellar glycine has NOT been confirmed** despite intensive searches. Kuan et al. (2003) claimed detection toward Sgr B2(N), but Snyder et al. (2005, *Astrophysical Journal* 619:914) rigorously refuted this. However, **aminoacetonitrile** \u2014 the direct Strecker precursor to glycine \u2014 was detected in Sgr B2(N) by Belloche et al. (2008, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*) at column density 2.8 \u00d7 10\u00b9\u2076 cm\u207b\u00b2, and interstellar glycolonitrile was detected toward the solar-type protostar IRAS 16293-2422 by Zeng et al. (2019, *MNRAS* 484:L43\u2013L48).\n\nLaboratory UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs consistently produces glycine as the most abundant amino acid. Bernstein, Dworkin, Sandford, and Allamandola (2002, *Nature* 416:401\u2013403) at NASA Ames showed that UV photolysis of H\u2082O:CH\u2083OH:NH\u2083:HCN ices at ~15 K produces racemic glycine, alanine, and serine. Simultaneously, Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416:403\u2013406) obtained **16 amino acids** from UV irradiation of ices without HCN, demonstrating that radical-radical pathways operate independently of Strecker chemistry. Elsila et al. (2007, *Astrophysical Journal* 660:911\u2013918) used isotopic labeling to confirm that multiple formation mechanisms \u2014 not purely Strecker \u2014 are operative in ices.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts concentrate reactants, drive reactions, and protect products across every pathway\n\nThe mineral catalyst landscape for prebiotic glycine synthesis spans four major categories, each with distinct mechanistic roles.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** form the catalytic core of hydrothermal vent chemistry. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to biological [4Fe-4S] clusters in ferredoxins, catalyzes CO\u2082 fixation and is thermodynamically stable as nanoparticles (Navrotsky et al., 2020, *PNAS*). Pyrite (FeS\u2082) provides thermodynamic driving force through its exergonic formation, while mackinawite (FeS) serves as the first-precipitated iron sulfide in hydrothermal systems and precursor to both greigite and pyrite. Yamaguchi et al. (2014, *Electrochimica Acta* 141:311\u2013318) showed that Ni-substituted greigite (forming violarite, FeNi\u2082S\u2084) substantially improves electrochemical CO\u2082 reduction efficiency.\n\n**Clay minerals**, first proposed by Bernal (1951) as prebiotic concentrators, play crucial roles in both concentration and catalysis. Montmorillonite's expanding interlayer (14\u201318 \u00c5 d-spacing) adsorbs amino acids from dilute solution and catalyzes their polymerization. Paecht-Horowitz (1976, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 7:369\u2013381) demonstrated peptide formation up to **40-mers** on montmorillonite (vs. 4\u20136 mers without clay). Fraser et al. (2017, *Nature Communications*) showed layered double hydroxides concentrate, align, and template amino acids during wet-dry cycles.\n\n**Photocatalytic minerals** drive UV-dependent pathways. Rutile TiO\u2082 (band gap 3.0 eV) ranks as the most effective mineral for glycine polymerization (Kitadai et al., 2017, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). Senanayake and Idriss (2006, *PNAS* 103:1194\u20131198) demonstrated that TiO\u2082(001) converts formamide to nucleobases and amino acids under UV, with activation energy <10 kJ/mol. ZnS (band gap ~3.6 eV) catalyzes **reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids** \u2014 glyoxylate \u2194 glycine \u2014 under UV illumination (Wang et al., 2012, *Chemical Communications* 48:2146\u20132148), mimicking amino acid dehydrogenase enzymes.\n\n**Transition metal surfaces** from serpentinization and meteoritic sources provide heterogeneous catalysis. Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe), which forms in serpentinized ultramafic rocks, catalyzes CO\u2082 \u2192 formate/acetate/pyruvate at 100\u00b0C (Preiner et al., 2020) and even at 25\u00b0C/25 bar (Beyazay et al., 2023). A critical general role of mineral surfaces is **product sequestration**: the 2024 PNAS ferroan brucite study found 97% of synthesized glycine bound to the mineral, detectable only after acid digestion \u2014 meaning previous experiments may have dramatically underestimated prebiotic amino acid yields by analyzing only solution phases.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions determine which pathways dominate at each synthesis step\n\nThe optimal environment varies by reaction step, creating a natural geochemical flow network:\n\n| Synthesis step | Optimal environment | Key conditions |\n|---|---|---|\n| CO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2081 compounds (formate, CO, HCHO) | Alkaline hydrothermal vents | 100\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311, greigite/magnetite/awaruite catalysts |\n| HCN synthesis | Atmosphere (spark/UV) | Reducing or CO-containing atmosphere + energy input |\n| NH\u2083 production | Atmosphere or mineral surfaces | Lightning/UV in reducing atmosphere; TiO\u2082 photoreduction of N\u2082; ferroan brucite reduction of nitrate |\n| Strecker synthesis (HCHO + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine) | Ice eutectic or warm ponds | \u221223\u00b0C eutectic for HCN concentration; or mineral-catalyzed warm ponds |\n| Reductive amination (glyoxylate + NH\u2083 \u2192 glycine) | Serpentinite systems | Ferroan brucite, pH 8\u20139, low-moderate T |\n| Glycine oligomerization | Wet-dry cycling on clays | pH 9.8, 140\u00b0C optimum for dimerization; montmorillonite at 80\u2013150\u00b0C |\n| Product protection | Clay interlayers or ice matrices | Interlayer confinement; low temperature |\n\nThe **ice/eutectic concentration mechanism** deserves special emphasis. Freezing dilute HCN to \u221223.4\u00b0C produces a eutectic with 74.5 mol% HCN (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966), enabling polymerization from solutions far too dilute for warm-ocean chemistry. Levy et al. (2000) detected adenine, guanine, and glycine from NH\u2084CN solutions frozen for 25 years at \u221220\u00b0C and \u221278\u00b0C. The 210\u2013273 K range maintains liquid eutectic brines in ice matrices while protecting products from thermal decomposition (Menor-Salv\u00e1n & Mar\u00edn-Yaseli, 2012, *Chemical Society Reviews* 41:5404\u20135415).\n\n---\n\n## Critical open questions, bottlenecks, and active debates shape the field's frontiers\n\n**The concentration problem** remains the most fundamental challenge. Oceanic HCN concentrations of ~2 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2076 M at 0\u00b0C (Miyakawa et al., 2002) are orders of magnitude below the 0.01\u20130.1 M threshold for productive chemistry. Five concentration mechanisms have experimental support: eutectic freezing (concentrating HCN by >10\u2076-fold), mineral surface adsorption (up to 97% sequestration), wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools, hydrothermal vent micro-compartments, and \u2014 most recently \u2014 **thermophoretic accumulation** through crack-like geo-compartments, which Matreux et al. (2024, *Nature* 628:110\u2013116) showed can boost concentration ratios by up to **1,000\u00d7** for >50 prebiotically relevant compounds.\n\n**The atmosphere composition debate** remains partially unresolved. Trail, Watson, and Tailby (2011, *Nature* 480:79\u201382) used cerium oxidation states in Hadean zircons (\u22654,350 Myr old) to demonstrate that volcanic outgassing was consistent with CO\u2082/N\u2082/H\u2082O rather than CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082. Yet Hashimoto et al. (2007) and Zahnle, Schaefer & Fegley (2010, *Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology* 2:a004895) argued that transient strongly reducing episodes after large impacts could sustain productive chemistry. The current synthesis position holds that **Earth's background atmosphere was weakly reducing (CO\u2082/N\u2082) but experienced transient reducing episodes** that provided windows for Miller-Urey-type chemistry.\n\n**The water problem** \u2014 thermodynamic unfavorability of condensation reactions in aqueous solution \u2014 primarily constrains glycine polymerization rather than its synthesis. Peptide bond formation costs **\u0394G \u2248 +3.5 kcal/mol** in water. Solutions include wet-dry cycling (Lahav et al., 1978, *Science* 201:67\u201369), air-water interfaces reducing water activity (Griffith & Vaida, 2012, *PNAS* 109:15697), mineral surface drying (Lambert, 2013), aqueous microdroplet chemistry (Cooks et al., 2024), and high-pressure hydrothermal conditions \u2014 Imai et al. (1999, *Science* 283:831) synthesized oligoglycines up to **decaglycine** at 270\u00b0C, 10 MPa, 27-second residence time.\n\n**Competing reactions** siphon precursors away from glycine: formaldehyde undergoes the formose reaction producing sugars and tar; HCN hydrolysis destroys cyanide before polymerization at low concentrations; Maillard reactions between amino acids and reducing sugars generate melanoidin polymers. The \"messy chemistry\" problem \u2014 prebiotic reactions producing complex mixtures rather than specific targets \u2014 is increasingly addressed through geological filtering, photochemical selection (UV degrading undesired products), and thermophoretic purification.\n\n---\n\n## Toward computational pathway design: what the network structure reveals\n\nThe prebiotic glycine synthesis network is not a collection of independent pathways but an interconnected web with identifiable hubs. **HCN** is the master node, feeding amino acids (Strecker), purines (Or\u00f3's adenine pentamer), pyrimidines (via oligomer hydrolysis), and lipid precursors (cyanosulfidic reductive homologation). **Formaldehyde** bridges sugar chemistry (formose reaction) and amino acid chemistry (Strecker) through glycolonitrile, which also accelerates HCN oligomerization ~5-fold (Schwartz & Goverde, 1982). **Aminoacetonitrile** serves as both the direct Strecker precursor to glycine and a reservoir molecule with UV half-life ~1,300 years in diffuse interstellar conditions, more stable than glycine itself.\n\nFor computational pathway generation systems like AstroAgents/GenesisAgents, the key quantitative parameters are: Strecker pathway rate-limiting barrier of **31 kcal/mol** (amide hydrolysis); HCN polymerization threshold of **0.01 M**; glycine thermal half-life of minutes at 250\u00b0C but years at 100\u00b0C; optimal dimerization at pH 9.8/140\u00b0C with Ea = 88 kJ/mol; and the recent ML-discovered \"oxyglycolate pathway\" (Huet et al., 2024, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters* 15:8697\u20138705) with a lowest rate-determining barrier of **51.2 kcal/mol** for direct glycine formation from CO/H\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083. The emerging computational frontier \u2014 ML-based interatomic potentials enabling near-quantum-accuracy exploration at reduced cost (Anton et al., 2025, *ChemSystemsChem*; Benayad et al., 2024, *PNAS* 121:e2322040121) \u2014 promises to map unexplored regions of the prebiotic reaction network, but faces the methodological challenge that training these models requires some prior knowledge of the pathways they seek to discover.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe evidence overwhelmingly establishes glycine as the most thermodynamically and kinetically accessible amino acid under prebiotic conditions \u2014 a conclusion reinforced by its dominance across every experimental system and extraterrestrial detection. The field has matured from isolated pathway studies to systems chemistry, recognizing that glycine synthesis cannot be divorced from the broader network producing nucleotides, lipids, and cofactors from shared HCN/HCHO/NH\u2083 feedstocks. The most productive frontier lies at the intersection of three developments: ferroan brucite/serpentinization chemistry expanding viable environments to include oxidizing atmospheres, cyanosulfidic network chemistry demonstrating unified origin of all three biopolymer classes, and thermophoretic geo-compartment concentration solving the dilution problem quantitatively. For computational pathway design, the network's hub-and-spoke architecture around HCN, formaldehyde, and aminoacetonitrile, combined with the well-characterized barrier heights and environmental constraints cataloged here, provides a structured foundation for algorithmic exploration of prebiotic synthesis space.", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_claude/Glycine-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_claude", "length": 25240}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-12T07:00:40.954665", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glycine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Glycine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS  ===\n# Prebiotic glycine synthesis: a complete pathway atlas for origin of life chemistry\n\n**Glycine, the simplest amino acid, emerges through at least ten distinct prebiotic routes spanning every plausible early Earth environment \u2014 from spark-discharge atmospheres to alkaline hydrothermal vents to interstellar ices.** This convergence from multiple independent pathways explains why glycine is consistently the most abundant amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments, carbonaceous meteorites, and cometary samples alike. The synthesis network is anchored by three master precursors \u2014 HCN, formaldehyde, and ammonia \u2014 whose reactions with each other and with mineral catalysts generate glycine through Strecker synthesis, HCN polymer hydrolysis, reductive amination, photochemistry, and Fischer-Tropsch-type catalysis. Understanding these interconnected pathways, their environmental requirements, kinetic bottlenecks, and shared intermediates is essential for computationally modeling prebiotic chemistry networks.\n\n---\n\n## The Strecker synthesis remains the dominant pathway to prebiotic glycine\n\nThe Strecker synthesis \u2014 formaldehyde + HCN + ammonia \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine \u2014 is the single most important route to prebiotic glycine, operating as the principal mechanism in Miller-Urey experiments, meteorite parent bodies, and potentially in interstellar ices. Stanley Miller himself identified this as the mechanism underlying his 1953 spark discharge results (Miller, 1953, *Science* 117:528\u2013529; Miller, 1957, *Biochimica et Biophysica Acta*).\n\nThe mechanism proceeds through four steps with well-characterized energetics. First, ammonia attacks formaldehyde to produce aminomethanol (NH\u2082CH\u2082OH), which dehydrates to methanimine (CH\u2082=NH). Cyanide then adds to the imine, yielding aminoacetonitrile (NH\u2082CH\u2082CN). Finally, hydrolysis proceeds through glycinamide (NH\u2082CH\u2082CONH\u2082) to glycine. Ab initio molecular dynamics simulations by Magrino, Pietrucci, and Saitta (2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters* 12:2630\u20132637) mapped the complete free energy landscape in explicit aqueous solution: glycinonitrile formation has a rate-limiting barrier of **15 kcal/mol**, nitrile hydration to glycinamide requires **23 kcal/mol**, and the final amide hydrolysis to glycine faces the highest barrier at **31 kcal/mol**. The overall reaction is strongly exergonic, with glycine at **\u221237 kcal/mol** relative to initial reactants.\n\nA critical alternative exists through the **Bucherer-Bergs pathway**, where aminoacetonitrile reacts with CO\u2082 (abundant in the early atmosphere) to form hydantoin, which hydrolyzes to N-carbamoyl-glycine, then to glycine. Taillades, Commeyras, and colleagues (1998, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 28:61\u201377) demonstrated that under realistic prebiotic conditions \u2014 [HCN] and [HCHO] ~1 g/L, pH 8, 25\u00b0C, low [NH\u2083] \u2014 the system produces 99.9% glycolonitrile and only 0.1% aminoacetonitrile. However, CO\u2082 catalyzes conversion of that small aminoacetonitrile fraction to hydantoin, shifting equilibrium productively. Pulletikurti et al. (2022, *Nature Chemistry*) achieved **80% hydantoin yield** from pyruvate + cyanide + ammonia in bicarbonate buffer at room temperature, demonstrating this pathway bridges prebiotic aldehyde chemistry and modern metabolism.\n\n---\n\n## Miller-Urey experiments and their modern reanalyses reveal far richer chemistry than originally appreciated\n\nMiller's original 1953 experiment \u2014 continuous spark discharge through CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082 for one week \u2014 identified five amino acids, with **glycine as the most abundant at ~1.05% of total carbon** (Miller, 1955, *Journal of the American Chemical Society*). The mechanism was purely chemical: sparks produced HCN and aldehydes in the gas phase, which dissolved and underwent Strecker synthesis in the aqueous flask.\n\nThe 2008 reanalysis by Jeffrey Bada's group transformed our understanding. After Miller's death in 2007, Bada inherited sealed sample vials from three distinct experimental setups. Using modern HPLC-MS and UPLC-ToF-MS, Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322:404) found that the classic experiment actually produced **14 amino acids and 5 amines** \u2014 far more than Miller's 1950s-era paper chromatography could detect. A previously unpublished volcanic spark discharge apparatus, using a steam-aspirating nozzle simulating volcanic lightning, yielded **22 amino acids and 5 amines**, many hydroxylated. Most remarkably, Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) reanalyzed Miller's 1958 H\u2082S-containing experiment and found **23 amino acids, 4 amines, and 7 organosulfur compounds** \u2014 with amino acid distributions that correlated remarkably well with carbonaceous chondrite abundances.\n\nThe atmospheric composition debate profoundly affects these yields. Under strongly reducing conditions (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082), glycine yields reach several percent of total carbon. Under neutral CO\u2082/N\u2082/H\u2082O atmospheres, yields plummet by orders of magnitude \u2014 though Cleaves et al. (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 38:105\u2013115) showed that adding ferrous iron as an oxidation inhibitor during hydrolysis substantially increased detected amino acids, suggesting previous low yields from neutral atmospheres were partly analytical artifacts. Schlesinger and Miller (1983, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*) demonstrated that **CO-containing atmospheres yield bioorganic compounds comparable to strongly reducing atmospheres**, an important finding since CO is geochemically more plausible than CH\u2084 as a long-lived atmospheric constituent.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents, serpentinization, and iron-sulfur mineral catalysis provide submarine routes to glycine\n\nTwo fundamentally different hydrothermal environments offer glycine synthesis potential, with alkaline vents dramatically more favorable than black smokers.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City type) operate at **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with H\u2082 concentrations up to **15 mmol/kg** generated by serpentinization of olivine. The Russell-Martin-Lane model proposes these vents as the cradle of prebiotic chemistry: natural pH gradients of ~5 units across thin Fe(Ni)S mineral barriers between alkaline vent fluid and the mildly acidic Hadean ocean (pH ~5.5) create electrochemical potentials of ~180 mV \u2014 directly analogous to biological chemiosmotic coupling. Wimmer et al. (2021) calculated that **97% of the ~400 reactions needed to synthesize amino acids, nucleobases, and cofactors are exergonic** under serpentinizing vent conditions.\n\nThe mineral catalysis results are striking. **Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 4:534\u2013542)** demonstrated that greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084), and awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) catalyze CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 formate (up to **200 mM**), acetate (~100 \u00b5M), pyruvate (~10 \u00b5M), and methanol (~100 \u00b5M) at 100\u00b0C under alkaline conditions. Even more remarkably, **Beyazay et al. (2023, *Nature Communications* 14:570)** showed Ni\u2083Fe nanoparticles catalyze CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate and citramalate at just **25\u00b0C under 25 bar** \u2014 room temperature catalysis on a mineral that forms naturally in serpentinizing systems.\n\nThe path from these C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 intermediates to glycine proceeds via reductive amination. **Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116:4828\u20134833)** demonstrated that pyruvate + NH\u2083 + mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides produces alanine, with maximum yield at **1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio** and alkaline pH. A landmark 2024 study in *PNAS* (doi:10.1073/pnas.2408248121) showed that **ferroan brucite** [Fe\u2080.\u2083\u2083Mg\u2080.\u2086\u2087(OH)\u2082] mediates glycine synthesis from nitrate + glyoxylate, with up to **97% of produced glycine partitioned to the mineral fraction** \u2014 demonstrating both synthesis and concentration in a single mineral system. This finding is particularly significant because it expands plausible prebiotic environments to include oxidizing atmospheres where nitrate is stable.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133) face a fundamental problem: glycine's thermal stability. Aqueous glycine decomposes via decarboxylation (\u2192 methylamine + CO\u2082) and deamination (\u2192 glycolic acid + NH\u2083), with activation energy **Ea \u2248 95.9\u2013156 kJ/mol** (Sato et al., 2004). At 200\u00b0C, ~90% of amino acids decompose; at 250\u00b0C, the half-life drops to minutes. The thermal optimum for glycine dimerization is **pH 9.8, 140\u00b0C**, with Ea = 88 kJ/mol (Sakata et al., 2010, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 74:6841\u20136851). These data strongly favor alkaline vents over black smokers for sustained amino acid chemistry.\n\nW\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis proposed that the exergonic formation of pyrite (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082, **\u0394G = \u22129.2 to \u221210.0 kcal/mol**) could drive prebiotic carbon fixation. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997, *Science* 276:245\u2013247) demonstrated thioester synthesis from CO + CH\u2083SH on FeS/NiS at 100\u00b0C, and subsequently showed peptide bond formation from amino acids activated with CO on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces (1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672). However, the proposed full autocatalytic reductive citric acid cycle on FeS surfaces has not been experimentally demonstrated, and Schoonen et al. (1999) could not replicate citric acid synthesis from CO\u2082 on FeS catalysts.\n\n---\n\n## HCN polymers, cyanosulfidic chemistry, and Fischer-Tropsch catalysis provide additional convergent pathways\n\n**HCN polymerization** represents a distinct route to glycine that bypasses the Strecker synthesis entirely. HCN oligomerizes through a base-catalyzed pathway: dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 trimer (aminomalononitrile, AMN) \u2192 tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2192 higher polymers. The rate-determining dimerization step has k = **0.096 L mol\u207b\u00b9 day\u207b\u00b9** at pH 9.2 and 40\u00b0C (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966, *Science* 153:72). A critical threshold exists: polymerization is fourth-order in HCN while hydrolysis is first-order, so polymerization dominates only above **0.01\u20130.1 M HCN** (Sanchez et al., 1967, *Journal of Molecular Biology* 30:223). Since oceanic HCN at 100\u00b0C and pH 8 reaches only ~7 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 32:209), eutectic concentration by freezing to **\u221223.4\u00b0C** (producing **74.5 mol% HCN** eutectic) is likely required.\n\nAcid or base hydrolysis of HCN polymers yields **glycine as the most abundant product under all 23 experimental conditions tested** (Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013, *Life* 3:421), alongside up to 24 amino acids total, including **12 of the 20 protein amino acids**. Or\u00f3's pioneering work in the early 1960s first demonstrated this, heating 0.1\u20132.2 M ammoniacal HCN at 70\u00b0C for 25 days. Matthews and Moser (1966, *PNAS* 56:1087) proposed that HCN polymerizes directly to polyaminomalononitrile and thence to heteropolypeptides without free amino acid intermediates \u2014 a controversial hypothesis challenged by Ferris (1979, *Science* 203:1135) but never fully resolved.\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry** represents the most elegant systems chemistry approach. Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307) demonstrated that HCN + H\u2082S + UV light + phosphate buffer at 35\u00b0C produces precursors to amino acids, ribonucleotides, and lipids simultaneously through a unified network. The mechanism involves Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox cycling driving reductive homologation of HCN, with H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant. Aminoacetonitrile (glycine precursor), 2-aminopropanenitrile (alanine precursor), and sugar precursors emerge as inevitable products of the same network. As Patel et al. noted, \"biology did not select all of its building blocks, but was simply presented with a specific set as a consequence of the (photo)chemistry of hydrogen cyanide and hydrogen sulfide.\"\n\n**Fischer-Tropsch type (FTT) synthesis** operates through CO + H\u2082 + NH\u2083 on metallic catalysts at 360\u2013600\u00b0C. Yoshino, Hayatsu, and Anders (1971, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 35:927\u2013938) first demonstrated amino acid synthesis including glycine on meteoritic iron catalysts. The mechanism involves FTT generation of formaldehyde and HCN on catalyst surfaces, followed by Strecker synthesis in cooler zones. In a CO-rich early atmosphere, native iron and FeNi particles could produce up to **7 \u00d7 10\u2079 to 5 \u00d7 10\u00b9\u00b2 kg/yr** of HCN and other organics.\n\n---\n\n## Glycine is ubiquitous in the solar system \u2014 from meteorites to comets to laboratory ice analogs\n\n**The Murchison meteorite** (CM2 carbonaceous chondrite, fell September 28, 1969, Australia) contains **>90 amino acids** at concentrations of ~3 ppm for glycine (~150\u2013250 nmol/g). Isotopic analysis provides definitive evidence of extraterrestrial origin: \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C values reach **+40\u2030** for amino acids (vs. terrestrial values typically <\u221220\u2030), with \u03b4D up to **+2,500\u2030** and near-racemic D/L ratios confirming abiotic synthesis (Cronin & Pizzarello, 1983; Pizzarello et al., 2004; Glavin & Dworkin, 2009, *PNAS* 106:5487). CR2 chondrites show even higher total amino acid concentrations, up to **~715 nmol/g** in some samples. The Strecker synthesis on aqueous parent bodies is supported by the dominance of \u03b1-amino acids and parallel production of \u03b1-hydroxy acids via the cyanohydrin pathway.\n\nCometary glycine was confirmed by two independent missions. The NASA **Stardust** spacecraft returned samples from Comet 81P/Wild 2 in 2006; Elsila, Glavin, and Dworkin (2009, *Meteoritics & Planetary Science* 44:1323\u20131330) detected glycine with extraterrestrial \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C signatures on collector surfaces. The ESA **Rosetta** mission directly measured glycine in the coma gas of Comet 67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko using the ROSINA mass spectrometer (Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances* 2:e1600285), along with methylamine and ethylamine (glycine precursors) and the first cometary detection of phosphorus.\n\n**Interstellar glycine has NOT been confirmed** despite intensive searches. Kuan et al. (2003) claimed detection toward Sgr B2(N), but Snyder et al. (2005, *Astrophysical Journal* 619:914) rigorously refuted this. However, **aminoacetonitrile** \u2014 the direct Strecker precursor to glycine \u2014 was detected in Sgr B2(N) by Belloche et al. (2008, *Astronomy & Astrophysics*) at column density 2.8 \u00d7 10\u00b9\u2076 cm\u207b\u00b2, and interstellar glycolonitrile was detected toward the solar-type protostar IRAS 16293-2422 by Zeng et al. (2019, *MNRAS* 484:L43\u2013L48).\n\nLaboratory UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs consistently produces glycine as the most abundant amino acid. Bernstein, Dworkin, Sandford, and Allamandola (2002, *Nature* 416:401\u2013403) at NASA Ames showed that UV photolysis of H\u2082O:CH\u2083OH:NH\u2083:HCN ices at ~15 K produces racemic glycine, alanine, and serine. Simultaneously, Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416:403\u2013406) obtained **16 amino acids** from UV irradiation of ices without HCN, demonstrating that radical-radical pathways operate independently of Strecker chemistry. Elsila et al. (2007, *Astrophysical Journal* 660:911\u2013918) used isotopic labeling to confirm that multiple formation mechanisms \u2014 not purely Strecker \u2014 are operative in ices.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts concentrate reactants, drive reactions, and protect products across every pathway\n\nThe mineral catalyst landscape for prebiotic glycine synthesis spans four major categories, each with distinct mechanistic roles.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** form the catalytic core of hydrothermal vent chemistry. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to biological [4Fe-4S] clusters in ferredoxins, catalyzes CO\u2082 fixation and is thermodynamically stable as nanoparticles (Navrotsky et al., 2020, *PNAS*). Pyrite (FeS\u2082) provides thermodynamic driving force through its exergonic formation, while mackinawite (FeS) serves as the first-precipitated iron sulfide in hydrothermal systems and precursor to both greigite and pyrite. Yamaguchi et al. (2014, *Electrochimica Acta* 141:311\u2013318) showed that Ni-substituted greigite (forming violarite, FeNi\u2082S\u2084) substantially improves electrochemical CO\u2082 reduction efficiency.\n\n**Clay minerals**, first proposed by Bernal (1951) as prebiotic concentrators, play crucial roles in both concentration and catalysis. Montmorillonite's expanding interlayer (14\u201318 \u00c5 d-spacing) adsorbs amino acids from dilute solution and catalyzes their polymerization. Paecht-Horowitz (1976, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres* 7:369\u2013381) demonstrated peptide formation up to **40-mers** on montmorillonite (vs. 4\u20136 mers without clay). Fraser et al. (2017, *Nature Communications*) showed layered double hydroxides concentrate, align, and template amino acids during wet-dry cycles.\n\n**Photocatalytic minerals** drive UV-dependent pathways. Rutile TiO\u2082 (band gap 3.0 eV) ranks as the most effective mineral for glycine polymerization (Kitadai et al., 2017, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). Senanayake and Idriss (2006, *PNAS* 103:1194\u20131198) demonstrated that TiO\u2082(001) converts formamide to nucleobases and amino acids under UV, with activation energy <10 kJ/mol. ZnS (band gap ~3.6 eV) catalyzes **reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids** \u2014 glyoxylate \u2194 glycine \u2014 under UV illumination (Wang et al., 2012, *Chemical Communications* 48:2146\u20132148), mimicking amino acid dehydrogenase enzymes.\n\n**Transition metal surfaces** from serpentinization and meteoritic sources provide heterogeneous catalysis. Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe), which forms in serpentinized ultramafic rocks, catalyzes CO\u2082 \u2192 formate/acetate/pyruvate at 100\u00b0C (Preiner et al., 2020) and even at 25\u00b0C/25 bar (Beyazay et al., 2023). A critical general role of mineral surfaces is **product sequestration**: the 2024 PNAS ferroan brucite study found 97% of synthesized glycine bound to the mineral, detectable only after acid digestion \u2014 meaning previous experiments may have dramatically underestimated prebiotic amino acid yields by analyzing only solution phases.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions determine which pathways dominate at each synthesis step\n\nThe optimal environment varies by reaction step, creating a natural geochemical flow network:\n\n| Synthesis step | Optimal environment | Key conditions |\n|---|---|---|\n| CO\u2082 \u2192 C\u2081 compounds (formate, CO, HCHO) | Alkaline hydrothermal vents | 100\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311, greigite/magnetite/awaruite catalysts |\n| HCN synthesis | Atmosphere (spark/UV) | Reducing or CO-containing atmosphere + energy input |\n| NH\u2083 production | Atmosphere or mineral surfaces | Lightning/UV in reducing atmosphere; TiO\u2082 photoreduction of N\u2082; ferroan brucite reduction of nitrate |\n| Strecker synthesis (HCHO + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine) | Ice eutectic or warm ponds | \u221223\u00b0C eutectic for HCN concentration; or mineral-catalyzed warm ponds |\n| Reductive amination (glyoxylate + NH\u2083 \u2192 glycine) | Serpentinite systems | Ferroan brucite, pH 8\u20139, low-moderate T |\n| Glycine oligomerization | Wet-dry cycling on clays | pH 9.8, 140\u00b0C optimum for dimerization; montmorillonite at 80\u2013150\u00b0C |\n| Product protection | Clay interlayers or ice matrices | Interlayer confinement; low temperature |\n\nThe **ice/eutectic concentration mechanism** deserves special emphasis. Freezing dilute HCN to \u221223.4\u00b0C produces a eutectic with 74.5 mol% HCN (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966), enabling polymerization from solutions far too dilute for warm-ocean chemistry. Levy et al. (2000) detected adenine, guanine, and glycine from NH\u2084CN solutions frozen for 25 years at \u221220\u00b0C and \u221278\u00b0C. The 210\u2013273 K range maintains liquid eutectic brines in ice matrices while protecting products from thermal decomposition (Menor-Salv\u00e1n & Mar\u00edn-Yaseli, 2012, *Chemical Society Reviews* 41:5404\u20135415).\n\n---\n\n## Critical open questions, bottlenecks, and active debates shape the field's frontiers\n\n**The concentration problem** remains the most fundamental challenge. Oceanic HCN concentrations of ~2 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2076 M at 0\u00b0C (Miyakawa et al., 2002) are orders of magnitude below the 0.01\u20130.1 M threshold for productive chemistry. Five concentration mechanisms have experimental support: eutectic freezing (concentrating HCN by >10\u2076-fold), mineral surface adsorption (up to 97% sequestration), wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools, hydrothermal vent micro-compartments, and \u2014 most recently \u2014 **thermophoretic accumulation** through crack-like geo-compartments, which Matreux et al. (2024, *Nature* 628:110\u2013116) showed can boost concentration ratios by up to **1,000\u00d7** for >50 prebiotically relevant compounds.\n\n**The atmosphere composition debate** remains partially unresolved. Trail, Watson, and Tailby (2011, *Nature* 480:79\u201382) used cerium oxidation states in Hadean zircons (\u22654,350 Myr old) to demonstrate that volcanic outgassing was consistent with CO\u2082/N\u2082/H\u2082O rather than CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082. Yet Hashimoto et al. (2007) and Zahnle, Schaefer & Fegley (2010, *Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology* 2:a004895) argued that transient strongly reducing episodes after large impacts could sustain productive chemistry. The current synthesis position holds that **Earth's background atmosphere was weakly reducing (CO\u2082/N\u2082) but experienced transient reducing episodes** that provided windows for Miller-Urey-type chemistry.\n\n**The water problem** \u2014 thermodynamic unfavorability of condensation reactions in aqueous solution \u2014 primarily constrains glycine polymerization rather than its synthesis. Peptide bond formation costs **\u0394G \u2248 +3.5 kcal/mol** in water. Solutions include wet-dry cycling (Lahav et al., 1978, *Science* 201:67\u201369), air-water interfaces reducing water activity (Griffith & Vaida, 2012, *PNAS* 109:15697), mineral surface drying (Lambert, 2013), aqueous microdroplet chemistry (Cooks et al., 2024), and high-pressure hydrothermal conditions \u2014 Imai et al. (1999, *Science* 283:831) synthesized oligoglycines up to **decaglycine** at 270\u00b0C, 10 MPa, 27-second residence time.\n\n**Competing reactions** siphon precursors away from glycine: formaldehyde undergoes the formose reaction producing sugars and tar; HCN hydrolysis destroys cyanide before polymerization at low concentrations; Maillard reactions between amino acids and reducing sugars generate melanoidin polymers. The \"messy chemistry\" problem \u2014 prebiotic reactions producing complex mixtures rather than specific targets \u2014 is increasingly addressed through geological filtering, photochemical selection (UV degrading undesired products), and thermophoretic purification.\n\n---\n\n## Toward computational pathway design: what the network structure reveals\n\nThe prebiotic glycine synthesis network is not a collection of independent pathways but an interconnected web with identifiable hubs. **HCN** is the master node, feeding amino acids (Strecker), purines (Or\u00f3's adenine pentamer), pyrimidines (via oligomer hydrolysis), and lipid precursors (cyanosulfidic reductive homologation). **Formaldehyde** bridges sugar chemistry (formose reaction) and amino acid chemistry (Strecker) through glycolonitrile, which also accelerates HCN oligomerization ~5-fold (Schwartz & Goverde, 1982). **Aminoacetonitrile** serves as both the direct Strecker precursor to glycine and a reservoir molecule with UV half-life ~1,300 years in diffuse interstellar conditions, more stable than glycine itself.\n\nFor computational pathway generation systems like AstroAgents/GenesisAgents, the key quantitative parameters are: Strecker pathway rate-limiting barrier of **31 kcal/mol** (amide hydrolysis); HCN polymerization threshold of **0.01 M**; glycine thermal half-life of minutes at 250\u00b0C but years at 100\u00b0C; optimal dimerization at pH 9.8/140\u00b0C with Ea = 88 kJ/mol; and the recent ML-discovered \"oxyglycolate pathway\" (Huet et al., 2024, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters* 15:8697\u20138705) with a lowest rate-determining barrier of **51.2 kcal/mol** for direct glycine formation from CO/H\u2082/H\u2082O/NH\u2083. The emerging computational frontier \u2014 ML-based interatomic potentials enabling near-quantum-accuracy exploration at reduced cost (Anton et al., 2025, *ChemSystemsChem*; Benayad et al., 2024, *PNAS* 121:e2322040121) \u2014 promises to map unexplored regions of the prebiotic reaction network, but faces the methodological challenge that training these models requires some prior knowledge of the pathways they seek to discover.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe evidence overwhelmingly establishes glycine as the most thermodynamically and kinetically accessible amino acid under prebiotic conditions \u2014 a conclusion reinforced by its dominance across every experimental system and extraterrestrial detection. The field has matured from isolated pathway studies to systems chemistry, recognizing that glycine synthesis cannot be divorced from the broader network producing nucleotides, lipids, and cofactors from shared HCN/HCHO/NH\u2083 feedstocks. The most productive frontier lies at the intersection of three developments: ferroan brucite/serpentinization chemistry expanding viable environments to include oxidizing atmospheres, cyanosulfidic network chemistry demonstrating unified origin of all three biopolymer classes, and thermophoretic geo-compartment concentration solving the dilution problem quantitatively. For computational pathway design, the network's hub-and-spoke architecture around HCN, formaldehyde, and aminoacetonitrile, combined with the well-characterized barrier heights and environmental constraints cataloged here, provides a structured foundation for algorithmic exploration of prebiotic synthesis space.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"glycine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This synthesis network for glycine strictly follows established prebiotic pathways from peer-reviewed literature, spanning hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments. Ten distinct routes are included, each grounded in experimental or computational evidence. The network is built around three master hub molecules\u2014HCN, formaldehyde, and aminoacetonitrile\u2014that serve as nodes of convergence, with multiple interconnections, environmental flows, and mineral-catalyzed steps. Both Strecker and Bucherer-Bergs pathways, HCN polymer hydrolysis, Fischer-Tropsch-type catalysis, cyanosulfidic photochemistry, and hydrothermal reductive amination are featured, alongside concentration mechanisms (eutectic freezing, mineral adsorption) and product protection (clays, brucite). The network provides redundancy and metabolic relevance, illustrating why glycine is the most abundant amino acid across prebiotic settings, meteorites, comets, and laboratory simulations.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H\u2082\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dihydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CN/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2083\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2082O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2082CH\u2082CN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1H2,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2082OH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3NO/h1H3N\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2082CH\u2082OH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"aminomethanol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aminomethanol\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH5NO/c2-1-3/h1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH\u2082=NH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanimine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methanimine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH\u2082CH\u2082CONH